Halloween's been days ago, but meet the last of the blush squad and the second Echeveria, the 'Ghost Echeveria'! Even if it got a spooky common name, its real name is rather pretty, Echeveria lilacina.

The Echeveria lilacina have silvery-grey plump leaves with a particularly blue hue and a delicate blush of lilac under the sun. This rosebud shaped succulent is native to Nuevo Leon, northern Mexico.

Grab fast our last Echeveria lilacina now! (In picture: succulent code 004) #abanesucculent #sukulenbandung

Our second member of the blush squad is the Echeveria purple prince! The genus Echeveria itself includes over a hundred species of rosetted succulent plants from Mexico, Central and South America.

The name Echeveria was taken from 18th century Mexican botanical artist, Atanasio Echeverria y Godoy.

Grab our very own Echeveria purple prince fast as it is last in stock! (In picture: succulent code 030) #abanesucculent #sukulenbandung

Behold the first of our personal blush squad, the most beautiful of all, the Graptopetalum penandrum! Guess what, its common name IS 'Beautiful Graptopetalum'. Okay.

The genus name is derived from Greek words; 'graptos' meaning marked and 'petalon' meaning petals. You can see the markings on the petals, which makes this beautiful one also unique. The species name 'pentandrum' refers to the five stamens on this Mexican native succulent. (In picture: succulent code 027) #abanesucculent #sukulenbandung

And this is the last of our furry friend series today, Kalanchoe tomentosa! This 'Panda Plant' or 'Pussy Ears' or 'Chocolate Soldier' is native to the island of Madagascar.

Its white hair and reddish-brown edges are similar to the fur of a panda and the shape is somewhat similar to a cat's ear, hence the names. 'Tomentosa' means densely woolly or velvety. (In picture: succulent code 013) #abanesucculent #sukulenbandung

Meet furry friend number two, Cotyledon tomentosa! It got the cutest alias ever, 'Bear's Paw'. Aww.

It's native to the Cape Province, South Africa. Its leaves are ovate, thumb-sized, and soft with "teeth" at the tips. You can totally see where it got its name from. (In picture: succulent code 014) #abanesucculent #sukulenbandung

Say hello to our first furry friend, the Echeveria setosa! It is commonly called the 'Mexican Firecracker' as it originates from Mexico and looks like fireworks... The name 'setosa' is taken from 'seta', the Latin word for silk, mentioning the silk-like hair on its leaves. (In picture: succulent code 011) #abanesucculent #sukulenbandung
